Narrative: On April [XXX], 2022, while operating in autonomous mode with a safety operator in the driver's seat, a Pony.ai Autonomous Vehicle was parked in a parking lot when a passenger vehicle reversed into the Pony.ai vehicle. The Pony.ai vehicle sustained minor damage to the driver's side rear door. There were no injuries, the police were not called to the scene, and the Pony.ai vehicle was driven back to Pony.ai's Fremont facility.

TuSimple's position is that this event does not meet the criteria for reporting under the SGO.
Specifically, the L4 ADS was not in operation at any point in the 30 seconds prior to making contact with the concrete barrier.  
 
The event occurred as follows:
As the truck was being operated on the highway, within its mapped ODD, the driver and test engineer attempted to engage the ADS.  However, the ADS was not functional at that moment due to the computer unit not having been initialized, and should not have been attempted to be activated.  In short, this was a failed attempt to engage the system as a result of human error.  
 
The system has now been modified to prevent the ADS from attempting to engage unless the health of the system is fully functional to prevent human error from repeating this event.
 
When the erroneous attempt to engage occurred, the uninitialized vehicle control unit rotated the steering to the left, causing the truck to veer left.  The safety driver took control of the steering, and was able to steer accordingly, but not before the left front truck tire and left front quarter panel came into contact with the concrete barrier to the left of the lanes of travel.  
 
The contact resulted in a scuff to the left tire and damage to the radar unit extending from the left quarter panel.

"The contact owns a 2021 Mercedes-Benz S580. The contact stated while driving at 60 MPH, the contact pressed a button on the steering wheel to engage the cruise control function on the vehicle. The contact stated when driving past a mileage sign stating 40 MPH, the vehicle suddenly reduce in speed to 40 MPH, while the contact was on the highway in the fast lane. The contact was able to move the vehicle over to the side of the road waited a few minutes took off the cruise control function and reapplied it back on and continued to drive the vehicle again. After a few minutes when the contact was exiting off the highway and the contact drove past a sign that said 60 MPH when suddenly the vehicle automatically accelerated on its own which caused the contact to rear-end a parked vehicle in front of them. The air bags did not deploy or the S.O.S. signal did not turn on. The contact was injured where they broke two bones in the right foot, left knee injury, and whiplash on their neck due to the seat belt. There was medical treatment at the scene. A police report was filed. The vehicle was towed to a local dealer where the vehicle was inspected but could not diagnose the caused the failure. The vehicle was not repaired. The manufacturer was made of the failure. The failure mileage was approximately 976."

This supplemental "Other" Report is intended only to provide two minor technical corrections to Pony.ai's prior reports, in order to ensure the details of the written reports, as revised, are accurate. To facilitate a clear record, this "Other" Updated Report reproduces verbatim the narrative descriptions from the prior reports concerning this incident. UNEDITED NARRATIVE FROM ORIGINAL MONTHLY REPORT (11/[XXX]/21) AND AMENDED REPORT (11/[XXX]/21): On October [XXX], 2021, after turning right onto [XXX] from [XXX], the Pony.ai Autonomous Vehicle ("Pony.ai AV") performed a left lane change maneuver in autonomous mode (SAE L4). While performing the lane change, the Pony.ai AV came into contact with a center divider on [XXX] and the traffic sign that was posted on the divider. The Pony.ai AV suffered moderate damage to the front of the vehicle and the undercarriage. There were no injuries and no other vehicles involved. [XXX] were called to report the incident and the damaged street sign. Pony.ai has subsequently worked with local authorities to resolve all issues related to the damaged sign. Rather the Pony.ai AV was traveling straight on [XXX] and crossed through an intersection with [XXX] before entering the segment of [XXX] on which it changed lanes and subsequently had a collision (2) Pony.ai has updated the VIN number of the subject vehicle in the data fields above, as there was one digit that was incorrect in our original reports due to a clerical error.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Sunnyvale, CA.  The vehicle was traveling South-bound on [XXX], an eight-lane divided road, operated by the vehicles Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the drivers designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle moved to the right of the lane to turn right onto West-bound [XXX], a two-lane road, and made contact with a curb at approximately 13-miles per hour.  The safety driver was monitoring the behavior of a vehicle passing in the left lane for signs that it might enter subject vehicles path and did not see subject vehicle moving toward the curb in time to intervene and avoid contact.  During the incident, the safety driver disengaged the Automated Driving System, and then pulled the vehicle to the side of [XXX] and inspected the vehicle and curb for damage.  After the inspection, the safety driver drove the vehicle back to base with the Automated Driving System disengaged.  Subject vehicle did not sustain tire or wheel damage, but the contact resulted in misalignment.  No other agents were involved, no injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene. Post-Crash Information: In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the tires, curb, and alignment calibration information.

While performing a multi point turn and the North end of [XXX](a dead end read) the Waymo AV was in reverse at approximately 2mph, when it made contact with front driver side door of the the unoccupied parked passenger vehicle. The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode just before making contact, when the test drivers transitioned the vehicle back to manual mode. The contact caused minor scuffing and a small dent to the door handle on the drivers side door, and minor damage to the plastic sensor housing of the Waymo AV's rear passenger side. Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this under the request of No. 1 of the Standing General Order 2021-01 also as a duplicate report to the report submitted by Waymo [XXX]). Transdev may correct or supplement it's reporting with additional information as it may become available.No 10-day update to narrative.

Other than the addition of the zip code in which the incident occurred, the content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on September [XXX], 2021 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. On September [XXX], 2021 at 1:54 PM PDT, a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Tempe, AZ was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. While in autonomous mode, the Waymo AV began to enter the right lane of a protected double left turn lane (Lane 2) from northbound [XXX] to westbound [XXX]. A pickup truck heading southbound on [XXX] had completely crossed the double-yellow lines of the northbound double left turn lanes and positioned itself in the left lane of the double turn lane (Lane 1) facing the wrong direction against traffic and was preparing to make a left turn across Lane 2 and the other two northbound lanes into a shopping center parking lot on the east side of [XXX]. The Waymo AV was traveling in Lane 2 when the pickup truck began to initiate its left turn from Lane 1. The Waymo AV braked, and the trained human driver in the Waymo AV (in the drivers seating position), transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode. As the pickup truck made the left turn, the drivers side panels of the pickup truck made contact with the drivers side rear corner of the Waymo AV causing moderate damage to the Waymo AV. Damage to the pickup is currently unknown. At the time of contact, the Waymo AV was in manual mode.Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Waymo AV was towed from the scene. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date, which in this case was the next business day after a weekend.

Vehicle was moving forward and veered slightly to the left, making contact with the curb, resulting in a blown tire. Curb strike occurred during testing. There was human error involved in defining the desired vehicle pose in the lane, which led to a curb strike. We have since resolved this by fixing the desired pose.

Vehicle made a right turn and struck the curb, causing a blown tire.Vehicle elected a controller path mid corner, which caused the curb strike. We have assessed the localities where this could occur and are taking those turns in manual operation. We are currently testing a fix that will make our controller more aware of the curb to prevent future occurrences.

This report is an update to 30412-1138. A Cruise autonomous vehicle (Cruise AV), operating in autonomous mode, was traveling southbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX] . The Cruise AV was traveling 24.4 mph upon entering the intersection with [XXX] on a green light. As the Cruise AV continued through the intersection, a bicyclist traveling eastbound on [XXX] failed to stop for their red light and entered the intersection. Summary of incidentLeading up to the event, the autonomy system functioned as expected, following the route through the intersection, slowing appropriately for other road users and the red light.  Vehicle autonomous behavior was performing as expected and did not require a takeover.Description of event:16:17:30 May vehicle, traveling East on [XXX], in full working order with no errors, autonomously navigates the [XXX] and [XXX] intersection.16:17:35 May vehicle autonomously begins to slow to match the speed of a vehicle several car lengths ahead merging into our lane from the right.16:17:37 By means of an accelerator pedal push the vehicle is moved into manual mode by the safety operator - from this point forward, the vehicle remains under control of the safety operator.16:17:43 Manual acceleration command via the pedal increases.16:17:44 Safety operator manually continues straight which, due to the slight change in angle of the road, brings the May vehicle into contact with the first vehicle to the right.16:17:44 Safety operator manually applies brake.16:17:45 With the manual brake command now at maximum the May vehicle makes contact with the second vehicle.Vehicle indicators for manual or autonomy mode:The visual indicator for autonomy was functioning properly and as expected in the time leading up to and during the event.The audio communication device in the vehicle was functioning properly and was used to call for assistance and to report the incident.The audio beep to indicate a state change was functioning properly.The safety operator had some audio indication that he had exited autonomy and entered manual operation, and he had full visual indication on his dashboard.

At about 11:35 am our vehicle (car 1) was waiting behind a USPS truck to make an unprotected left turn, meanwhile one other vehicle (car 2) waited behind our vehicle.   Another non involved vehicle notices the queue of vehicles and passes on the right in the bike lane.  As the USPS truck begins to make the turn, car 1 begins to move forward at 7 MPH then slowed to 3 MPH when yielding to the vehicle passing in the bike lane. Car 2 directly behind us strikes our passenger rear bumper.  The safety driver then disengaged the vehicle (car 1) and moved into a nearby parking lot to exchange information.

On August [XXX], 2021 at approximately 4:48pm, Waymo Autonomous Vehicle operated by a Transdev employee, in the city of San Francisco, California was stuck by a bicycle at [XXX] and [XXX]. The Waymo AV had stopped at the stop sign on [XXX] and, when the intersection was clear, began to proceed westbound through the intersection with [XXX]. At the approximately the same time, a cyclist traveling northbound ran the stop sign on [XXX], began to turn right into [XXX] but immediately veered left to continue northbound across the crosswalk on [XXX], where it stuck the rear drivers side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist stated upright and immediately rode away, continuing northbound on [XXX]. The Bicyclist caused a minor scratches and marks on the rear divers side bumper of the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV was operating with a driver (in the driver's seating position), who transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode approximately 1 second before the impact occurred. At the time of impact, the Waymo AV was in manual mode. Trasndev Alternative Services (TAS) is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of the Standing General Order 2021-01 because of a vulnerable road user was involved. Transdev may supplement or correct it's reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate to Waymo LLC's report WaymoLLC-[XXX]).
